{
  "response": "# Accessible Modal Dialog with Form Validation \u2014 Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.\n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA\n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users (JAWS, NVDA, VoiceOver), keyboard-only users, low-vision users, users with cognitive load sensitivity, users who zoom to 400%.\n> **Assistive technologies:** JAWS (with Firefox/Chrome), NVDA (with Firefox/Chrome), VoiceOver (with Safari), keyboard-only navigation.\n\n**Feature:** A reusable Next.js modal dialog component that traps focus, restores focus on close, and hosts a form with field-level validation, live error announcements, and a submission success state.\n**Risk Level:** High \u2014 combines four high-risk patterns (modal overlay + focus trap + form validation + dynamic live-region announcements), supports nesting, and is reusable (a single defect propagates everywhere it is used).\n**Component Type:** Modal Dialog (APG Dialog/Modal) + Form with validation (APG form labeling and error patterns).\n\n---\n\n## Resolving the Ambiguity First\n\nThe fixture flags this as AMBIGUOUS and asks four questions. Accessibility design cannot proceed on \"we'll decide later,\" because the validation timing, field count, nesting model, and error-recovery flow each change the ARIA architecture. I am resolving each one with an explicit, defensible default. **If the team disagrees with any default below, STOP and revise the plan before implementation \u2014 these are load-bearing decisions, not cosmetic ones.**\n\n| Ambiguity | Decision (default) | Why this is the safe default | What changes if reversed |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Real-time (aria-live) or submit-time (aria-describedby) validation?** | **Both, layered.** Per-field errors are associated statically via `aria-describedby` + `aria-invalid` (always present in DOM, read on focus). They are *announced* via a controlled, debounced live region on blur and on submit \u2014 **not on every keystroke.** | Announcing on every keystroke spams the screen reader and is itself a WCAG 3.3.1 usability failure (errors fire before the user finishes typing). `aria-describedby` is the durable, re-navigable record; the live region is the just-in-time notification. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.3. | If \"on submit only,\" drop the on-blur live announcement and keep only the submit-time error-summary announcement. The `aria-describedby` association stays either way. |\n| **How many fields?** | **Treat as N (2\u201310), design for the general case.** The plan uses one error-summary live region + per-field `aria-describedby`, which scales from 2 to 10+ fields with **no per-field live regions** (see Known Pitfall #1). | A design that only works for 2 fields breaks at 10. A per-field-live-region design breaks at 2 (duplicate-region announcement bug). The summary + describedby model is field-count-agnostic. | None \u2014 this is deliberately count-independent. |\n| **Can modals be nested?** | **Yes \u2014 design for a stack.** Each modal manages its own focus trap and its own trigger-restore reference. Only the topmost modal is interactive; ancestors get `inert`. | The fixture constraints explicitly say \"Multiple modals can be stacked (nested).\" Designing for one and bolting on nesting later breaks focus restoration (focus restores to the wrong element). | If nesting is truly out of scope, the `inert`-the-ancestors and stack-of-restore-targets logic simplifies to a single restore target, but the rest is unchanged. |\n| **What is the error-recovery flow?** | On a failed submit: focus moves to the **first invalid field** (not the summary), each invalid field carries `aria-invalid=\"true\"` + `aria-describedby` pointing at its visible error, and a summary live region announces the count (\"3 errors. First error: Email is required.\"). As the user fixes each field, `aria-invalid` flips to `false` and the error text is removed from DOM on the next successful field-level validation. | WCAG 3.3.1 (identify the error) + 3.3.3 (suggest a fix) + 2.4.3 (focus order). Moving focus to the first invalid field is faster for keyboard users than moving to a summary and re-tabbing. | If product wants an error-summary-link pattern (jump links to each field), that is a valid alternative \u2014 see Phase 5 note. It is more work and only pays off at 6+ fields. |\n\n**Negative space (what this plan does NOT cover):** non-modal dialogs (`role=\"dialog\"` without `aria-modal`), alertdialogs for destructive confirmation (that is a different APG pattern \u2014 `role=\"alertdialog\"` \u2014 noted but not specified here), multi-step/wizard forms, file-upload fields, rich-text inputs, date pickers / comboboxes inside the form (each is its own APG pattern and would need its own plan), and drag-to-dismiss. If the hosted form contains a combobox or date picker, that child widget needs its own a11y-planner pass.\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\n**What:** A reusable React/Next.js `<Modal>` component (client component \u2014 it manages focus and DOM-level keyboard handlers, so it cannot be a Server Component) that renders an overlay, traps keyboard focus, restores focus to the trigger on close, and accepts arbitrary form content as children. The reference form inside it demonstrates label association, field-level validation, live error announcement, and a success state.\n\n**Why:** Modals and validated forms are the two most common sources of shipped accessibility defects (focus escapes the modal; focus doesn't restore; errors are shown in red but never announced; the dialog isn't announced as a dialog). Building this reusable and correct once prevents the same four bugs from recurring across the app.\n\n**Who needs accessibility:**\n- **Screen reader users** \u2014 must hear \"dialog,\" hear the dialog name, be moved into the dialog, be trapped inside it, hear validation errors, and hear the success message. JAWS/NVDA forms-mode vs browse-mode behavior matters here.\n- **Keyboard-only users** \u2014 must reach every control with Tab, never tab out of the modal to the page behind it, close with Escape, and have focus land somewhere sane on close.\n- **Low-vision / zoom users** \u2014 focus indicator must be visible at 400% zoom; the modal must reflow without horizontal scroll; error color must not be the only error signal.\n- **Cognitive-load users** \u2014 errors must be specific and suggest a fix, must not fire mid-typing, and must not vanish before they're read.\n\n**Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA. (Relevant 2.2-specific additions: 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured (Minimum) \u2014 the focused control inside the modal must not be hidden behind a sticky header or the modal chrome; 2.5.8 Target Size (Minimum) \u2014 the close \"X\" must be \u226524\u00d724 CSS px, and we target 44\u00d744.)\n\n**Assistive technologies to support:** JAWS + Chrome/Firefox, NVDA + Chrome/Firefox, VoiceOver + Safari, keyboard-only. Note the practical reality: `aria-modal=\"true\"` is well supported in current AT, but to support older AT and to make nesting robust we ALSO apply `inert` to the background \u2014 belt and suspenders (see Phase 4).\n\n**Risk level:** **High.** Justification: (1) focus trap is notoriously easy to get wrong (the catch-22 with `visibility:hidden`, tabbing into browser chrome, Shift+Tab from the first element); (2) live-region announcements are invisible to automated tools and to visual QA \u2014 they only surface in real AT testing; (3) nesting multiplies focus-restoration complexity; (4) reusability means every defect ships N times.\n\n**Constraints (from fixture):**\n- Validation can be **async** (e.g., server-side uniqueness check on an email) \u2192 must communicate a pending/busy state, not just success/error. This is a real gap most plans miss.\n- **Modals can be nested** \u2192 stack-aware focus management.\n- **Error recovery needed** \u2192 invalid fields must be recoverable and the recovery must be announced.\n\n**Platform constraints:** Next.js App Router. The modal is a Client Component (`\"use client\"`). It should render into a portal at the document body so the overlay isn't constrained by an ancestor's `overflow:hidden` or `transform` (a transformed ancestor breaks `position:fixed`). Server Components can pass the trigger and the form fields as children, but the modal shell itself is client-side.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\n### Landmarks and document context\n\nThe modal is **not** a landmark and must not introduce one. When open, it is an overlay layered on top of `main`. Critically: **when the modal is open, the rest of the page must be removed from the accessibility tree** so a screen reader user navigating by heading/landmark/arrow keys cannot wander out of the dialog into the page behind it. Two mechanisms, applied together:\n\n1. `aria-modal=\"true\"` on the dialog \u2014 tells AT \"the content outside this node is inert.\" WCAG 4.1.2.\n2. `inert` attribute on the background container (everything that is NOT the dialog) \u2014 actually removes it from focus order AND the a11y tree in supporting browsers. This is the durable mechanism; `aria-modal` alone has had spotty history and does not cover nested-modal ancestors.\n\n> Do NOT rely on `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on the background *instead of* `inert`. `aria-hidden` hides from the a11y tree but does **not** remove elements from the tab order \u2014 keyboard focus can still land on a background control (Known Pitfall: hidden content still receives focus). `inert` does both. WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3.\n\n### Heading hierarchy\n\nThe dialog's accessible name comes from a visible heading inside it, referenced by `aria-labelledby`. That heading's level depends on context, but the safe reusable choice is `<h2>` (the page `<h1>` is the page title; the dialog title is a section-level heading). The component should accept a configurable heading level prop with a default of `h2`, and must never skip levels relative to surrounding content. WCAG 1.3.1, 2.4.6.\n\n### Form structure\n\n- The form is a real `<form>` element. Submit is a real `<button type=\"submit\">` so Enter-to-submit works natively and the browser fires a submit event we can intercept. WCAG 2.1.1.\n- **Grouped inputs use `<fieldset>` + `<legend>`** when (and only when) fields form a semantic group (e.g., a \"Billing address\" group, or a radio group). Do **not** wrap every single input in its own fieldset \u2014 a lone text input does not need a fieldset, and over-grouping adds noise. The fixture asks for fieldset/legend \"for grouped inputs,\" which is exactly this conditional. WCAG 1.3.1.\n- **Every input has a visible `<label for>`** \u2014 see the Known Pitfall: a visible `<label>` is required; `aria-label`/`aria-labelledby` is not a substitute for a visible label on a form field. Both the visible label AND the programmatic association are specified per field. WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2.\n- Required fields: visible required indicator (text \"(required)\" or an asterisk WITH a legend explaining the asterisk \u2014 asterisk alone is a 1.3.1 borderline failure) PLUS `aria-required=\"true\"` (or the native `required` attribute, but `aria-required` is preferred when we manage validation ourselves so we control when the browser's native bubble does/doesn't fire). WCAG 3.3.2.\n\n### HTML structure stub (structure only \u2014 not implementation code)\n\n```\n[Portal \u2192 document.body]\n\n<div class=\"overlay\" data-overlay>            \u2190 visual scrim; click-to-close target (optional)\n  <div\n    role=\"dialog\"\n    aria-modal=\"true\"\n    aria-labelledby=\"dialog-title-{id}\"\n    aria-describedby=\"dialog-desc-{id}\"        \u2190 optional; only if there is intro text\n  >\n    <header>\n      <h2 id=\"dialog-title-{id}\">{title}</h2>\n      <button type=\"button\" data-close aria-label=\"Close dialog\">\n        <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u00d7</span>      \u2190 the \u00d7 glyph is decorative; name comes from aria-label\n      </button>\n    </header>\n\n    <p id=\"dialog-desc-{id}\">{optional intro/instructions}</p>\n\n    <form novalidate>                          \u2190 novalidate: we own validation + announcements\n      <!-- Optional grouping: -->\n      <fieldset>\n        <legend>{group name}</legend>\n\n        <div class=\"field\">\n          <label for=\"email-{id}\">Email address (required)</label>\n          <input\n            id=\"email-{id}\"\n            type=\"email\"\n            aria-required=\"true\"\n            aria-invalid=\"false\"               \u2190 flips to \"true\" on error\n            aria-describedby=\"email-hint-{id} email-error-{id}\"\n          >\n          <p id=\"email-hint-{id}\" class=\"hint\">We'll never share your email.</p>\n          <p id=\"email-error-{id}\" class=\"error\" hidden>{error text, rendered only when invalid}</p>\n        </div>\n\n        <!-- repeat .field per input -->\n      </fieldset>\n\n      <div class=\"actions\">\n        <button type=\"button\" data-close>Cancel</button>\n        <button type=\"submit\" aria-describedby=\"submit-status-{id}\">Submit</button>\n      </div>\n    </form>\n\n    <!-- ONE error-summary live region per dialog, not per field -->\n    <div id=\"error-summary-{id}\" role=\"alert\" aria-live=\"assertive\" class=\"visually-hidden-unless-errors\"></div>\n\n    <!-- ONE polite status region for pending/success -->\n    <div id=\"submit-status-{id}\" role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\" class=\"visually-hidden\"></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n```\n\nKey structural decisions baked into the stub:\n- **One `role=\"alert\"` region and one `role=\"status\"` region per dialog instance**, placed at the dialog level \u2014 never inside the `{% per-field %}` loop (Known Pitfall #1). The per-field `<p class=\"error\">` are **describedby targets**, not live regions; they are silent and only announce via the summary or on focus.\n- The error `<p>` is referenced by `aria-describedby` even while `hidden`. When empty/hidden, AT skips it; when populated, AT reads it on focus. Referencing a hidden element by id is valid and the reference does not break when the element toggles visibility.\n- The `\u00d7` close glyph is wrapped `aria-hidden=\"true\"`; the button's name is the `aria-label=\"Close dialog\"` (Known Pitfall #2: `aria-label`, never `title`).\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### APG patterns mapped (with citations)\n\n| Element | APG pattern | Spec URL |\n|---|---|---|\n| Modal shell, focus trap, Escape-to-close | **Dialog (Modal)** | https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/ |\n| Trigger button | **Button** | https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ |\n| Close / Cancel / Submit buttons | **Button** | https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ |\n| Field errors + status | Live-region guidance, not a widget pattern | https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/practices/alerting-the-user/ |\n| (If a destructive \"discard changes?\" confirm is added) | **Alert Dialog** | https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/alertdialog/ |\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard | ARIA | WCAG |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Trigger button | Button | Tab to focus; Enter/Space activates \u2192 opens modal | native `<button>`; on open, sets `aria-expanded` is NOT used (dialog isn't a disclosure) | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Dialog container | Dialog (Modal) | Receives focus on open; Escape closes; Tab/Shift+Tab cycle trapped inside | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"`, `aria-labelledby`, optional `aria-describedby` | 1.3.1, 2.1.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Close (X) button | Button | Tab to focus; Enter/Space closes | native `<button>`, `aria-label=\"Close dialog\"`; child `\u00d7` is `aria-hidden` | 2.1.1, 2.5.8, 4.1.2 |\n| Cancel button | Button | Tab to focus; Enter/Space closes | native `<button type=\"button\">` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit button | Button | Tab to focus; Enter/Space submits; Enter inside any text field also submits (native) | native `<button type=\"submit\">`; `aria-describedby=\"submit-status\"`; gets `aria-disabled=\"true\"` (not `disabled`) while async-submitting so it stays focusable and announces | 2.1.1, 4.1.2, 4.1.3 |\n| Text inputs | (native form control) | Tab to focus; type to edit | `<label for>`, `aria-required`, `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby` | 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n\n### Keyboard interaction model (the complete contract)\n\nPer the APG Dialog (Modal) pattern, **every branch** must be implemented (Known Pitfall #4: plan behavior for ALL code branches):\n\n- **Tab** from the last focusable element in the dialog \u2192 wraps to the first focusable element in the dialog.\n- **Shift+Tab** from the first focusable element in the dialog \u2192 wraps to the last focusable element in the dialog.\n- **Tab/Shift+Tab** never move focus to any element outside the dialog (page behind is `inert`).\n- **Escape** \u2192 closes the dialog (and restores focus \u2014 see Phase 4). For a **nested** modal, Escape closes **only the topmost** dialog and returns focus/control to the parent dialog, not all the way to the page.\n- **Enter** inside a single-line text field \u2192 submits the form (native behavior; do not suppress it). Inside a `<textarea>`, Enter inserts a newline (native).\n- **Enter/Space** on any button \u2192 activates it (native).\n- **Optional: click on the overlay scrim** \u2192 closes the dialog. If enabled, this must be **opt-in per modal**, and must NOT be the only way to close (keyboard users can't click a scrim) and must NOT be enabled for forms with unsaved input without a confirm (data-loss risk). Default: scrim click is **disabled** for this form modal because it hosts editable input.\n\n### Screen reader experience (the narrative)\n\n- **On open:** focus moves into the dialog \u2192 AT announces the dialog role and its accessible name, e.g., NVDA: *\"Sign up, dialog\"* then the first focusable element's name/role/state. (Where focus lands on open is a Phase 4 decision.)\n- **On reaching a field:** *\"Email address, required, edit, We'll never share your email\"* (label + required + role + hint via describedby). If the field is already invalid: *\"\u2026invalid entry, Email is required.\"*\n- **On blur of an invalid field:** the summary live region (assertive) announces the single new error. (We debounce so typing doesn't fire it.)\n- **On submit with errors:** assertive announcement *\"3 errors. First error: Email is required,\"* focus moves to the first invalid field.\n- **During async submit:** polite status announces *\"Submitting\u2026\"* then *\"Submitted successfully\"* or *\"Submission failed: {reason}.\"*\n- **On close:** focus returns to the trigger; AT announces the trigger button (the user is back where they started).\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\nThis is the highest-risk section. Each item below maps to a specific failure mode that ships when it's skipped.\n\n### Tab order\n\nLogical order inside the dialog, matching visual top-to-bottom (WCAG 2.4.3): Close (X) button \u2192 form fields in source order \u2192 Cancel \u2192 Submit. (Some teams put Close last in tab order; either is acceptable as long as DOM order matches visual order. Default: Close is first because it is visually top-right and first in the DOM header.) DOM order MUST equal visual order \u2014 do not reorder with CSS `order` or absolute positioning in a way that diverges from source. WCAG 1.3.2, 2.4.3.\n\n### Where focus goes ON OPEN\n\nDecision tree (the reusable component exposes an `initialFocus` prop; these are the defaults):\n1. If the dialog has a **destructive or high-consequence** primary action \u2192 focus the **dialog container itself** (`tabindex=\"-1\"` on the dialog) or the least-destructive button, so a stray Enter doesn't fire the dangerous action. (Not the case for this signup-style form.)\n2. **Default for this form modal:** focus the **first focusable form field** (the first input). Rationale: the user opened the modal to fill the form; landing on the first input is the fastest path and is announced with full context (name/role/required/hint). APG permits focusing the first interactive element.\n3. Never leave focus on the page behind the modal. Never focus a non-interactive element without making it programmatically focusable (`tabindex=\"-1\"`).\n\nCaveat (WCAG 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured): if the dialog has a sticky header and a long scrolling body, ensure the initially focused field is scrolled into view and not hidden behind the sticky header.\n\n### Focus trap (the mechanism)\n\n- On open, compute the set of focusable elements within the dialog (buttons, inputs, links, `[tabindex]:not([tabindex=\"-1\"])`, etc.). Maintain first and last.\n- Intercept Tab on the last element \u2192 move to first; Shift+Tab on the first \u2192 move to last.\n- **Prefer the `inert` approach over manual Tab interception where possible:** applying `inert` to every sibling of the dialog at the body level means the browser's native Tab simply cannot leave the dialog \u2014 no manual wrap math, and it's robust against dynamically added/removed focusables (async error `<p>`s appearing don't break a stale focusable list). Manual Tab interception is the fallback for browsers without `inert`, and even then `inert` + manual wrap is the most robust combination. WCAG 2.1.2 (No Keyboard Trap \u2014 note the trap must be escapable via Escape, which it is).\n- **Do not use `visibility:hidden` or `display:none` to \"hide\" any dialog control that should be reachable** \u2014 that removes it from the tab order (catch-22). Controls that are temporarily unavailable use `aria-disabled` (still focusable, still announced), not `disabled` and not visibility hiding. (Known Pitfall: reveal-on-hover and hidden-content focus traps.)\n\n### Nested / stacked modals\n\n- Maintain a **stack** of open dialogs. Only the **topmost** dialog is non-inert; ALL ancestors (including parent dialogs) and the page get `inert`.\n- Each dialog stores **its own** \"return focus to\" target (the element focused at the moment it opened \u2014 usually a button inside the parent dialog). Closing the top dialog restores focus to *its* stored target (a control in the parent dialog), not to the original page trigger.\n- Escape closes only the topmost dialog. WCAG 2.4.3.\n\n### Focus restoration ON CLOSE\n\n- Before opening, capture `document.activeElement` as the restore target and store it (per-dialog, on the stack).\n- On close (via Escape, Close button, Cancel, or successful submit-then-close), **return focus to the stored restore target**. WCAG 2.4.3.\n- Edge case: if the restore target has been removed from the DOM while the modal was open (e.g., the trigger was in a list row that got deleted), fall back to a sensible nearby element (the container that held the trigger, made focusable with `tabindex=\"-1\"`, or the page `<h1>`). Never leave focus on `document.body` (it strands screen reader users at the top with no context). This is the \"focus after CRUD\" pattern applied to the trigger itself.\n- React/Next timing: apply restoration in an effect cleanup, and if a re-render races the focus call, defer with a microtask/`setTimeout(\u2026, 0)` so focus lands after the modal unmounts. (Known Pitfall: framework re-render eats `.focus()`.)\n\n### Focus indicator\n\n- Visible focus ring on every control, **two-tone (outline + box-shadow)** so it's visible against both the dialog background and any control background. Use `:focus-visible`. Minimum 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors. WCAG 2.4.7, 2.4.11. Must remain visible at 400% zoom.\n\n### Skip links\n\nNot applicable inside the modal (it's small and fully trapped). The page itself should already have a skip-to-main link (WCAG 2.4.1), but that is outside this component's scope.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\nEvery state below is communicated **visually AND programmatically** (WCAG 1.4.1 \u2014 color is never the sole signal).\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual | Programmatic | ARIA / mechanism | WCAG |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Dialog open | Overlay scrim + dialog visible | Focus moved into dialog; background `inert` | `role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal=\"true\"` | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Dialog closed | Overlay gone | Focus restored to trigger | (dialog unmounted / hidden) | 2.4.3 |\n| Field valid (default) | Neutral border | \u2014 | `aria-invalid=\"false\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Field invalid | Red border **+ error icon + error text below** | error text rendered + associated | `aria-invalid=\"true\"`, `aria-describedby` includes error id | 1.4.1, 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Field required | Visible \"(required)\" text (not asterisk alone) | \u2014 | `aria-required=\"true\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| New error announced (on blur / submit) | (the visual error appears) | spoken once | summary region `role=\"alert\"` / `aria-live=\"assertive\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Submit pending (async) | Spinner + \"Submitting\u2026\" text + button visually busy | button stays focusable, announced busy | `aria-disabled=\"true\"` on submit + `role=\"status\"` says \"Submitting\u2026\"; optionally `aria-busy=\"true\"` on form | 4.1.3, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit success | Success banner/text, green + checkmark icon | spoken | `role=\"status\"` / `aria-live=\"polite\"`: \"Submitted successfully\" | 1.4.1, 4.1.3 |\n| Submit failure (server) | Error banner, red + icon | spoken assertively | `role=\"alert\"`: \"Submission failed: {reason}. {recovery action}.\" | 1.4.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.3 |\n| Field recovered (was invalid, now valid) | Red border + error text removed | `aria-invalid` \u2192 false; error `<p>` removed/hidden | (no announcement needed; absence is fine) | 4.1.2 |\n\n### Live region architecture (the part most plans get wrong)\n\nTwo regions per dialog, declared **empty and present in the DOM from first render** (a live region that is inserted into the DOM at the same time as its content often does NOT announce \u2014 the region must pre-exist so AT is already observing it):\n\n1. **Error summary** \u2014 `role=\"alert\"` (implicitly `aria-live=\"assertive\"`). Used for: the on-blur single-error announcement and the on-submit \"N errors, first error: \u2026\" announcement. Assertive because the user has just acted (blurred/submitted) and expects immediate feedback.\n2. **Submit status** \u2014 `role=\"status\"` (implicitly `aria-live=\"polite\"`). Used for: \"Submitting\u2026\", \"Submitted successfully\", and also as the `aria-describedby` target of the submit button so the status is associated with the button itself.\n\n**Hard rules for the live regions (Known Pitfalls #1, #4):**\n- Exactly **one** of each per dialog instance, at the dialog level. **Never** put `role=\"alert\"`/`aria-live` on the per-field error `<p>` \u2014 those repeat in a loop, and a live region inside a loop fires duplicate/garbled announcements. Per-field errors communicate via `aria-describedby` (on focus) only.\n- To re-announce the *same* message text (e.g., user submits twice with the same error), the text must actually change in the DOM or be cleared-then-set on a tick, or AT will treat identical text as \"no change\" and stay silent. Plan a clear\u2192set sequence.\n- Do not announce on every keystroke. Debounce field validation; announce on blur and on submit.\n\n### Async validation (the constraint most plans drop)\n\nThe fixture says validation can be async. That means a field can be in a **\"checking\u2026\"** state (e.g., verifying email uniqueness against the server). Plan:\n- While a field's async check is in flight, the **submit-status** polite region may say \"Checking email\u2026\" (optional, only if the wait is perceptible).\n- Do not flip `aria-invalid=\"true\"` until the async check resolves as invalid \u2014 flipping it prematurely lies to AT.\n- If the user submits while an async check is pending, the submit handler must await the result before announcing success/failure; announce \"Validating\u2026\" via the polite region so the user isn't met with silence.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n- **Contrast (WCAG 1.4.3):** dialog text 4.5:1; error text 4.5:1 against the dialog background (do not rely on the red error *color* meeting 3:1 \u2014 the error *text* needs 4.5:1 like any normal text); button labels 4.5:1; the scrim must darken the background enough that the dialog visibly stands out but the scrim color is decorative (no contrast requirement on the scrim itself). Focus ring 3:1 (1.4.11 Non-text Contrast).\n- **Color is never the only error signal (WCAG 1.4.1):** every invalid field has red border **+ an error icon + visible text below**. Required fields use the word \"(required),\" not color or asterisk alone. Success uses green **+ checkmark + \"Submitted successfully\" text.**\n- **Focus indicator (WCAG 2.4.7):** two-tone ring as in Phase 4. `:focus-visible`, not `:focus`. Inline controls use `display:inline-block` so the ring is a full rectangle.\n- **Target size (WCAG 2.5.8 / 2.2 AA):** the close \"X\" button is the classic violator \u2014 it must be \u226524\u00d724 CSS px (2.2 minimum) and we target **44\u00d744** for comfort. Cancel/Submit buttons comfortably exceed this.\n- **Resize / reflow (WCAG 1.4.4, 1.4.10):** dialog uses relative units (`rem`), `max-width: min(90vw, 32rem)` and `max-height: 90vh` with the **body of the dialog scrollable** (`overflow:auto`) so at 400% zoom / 320px-equivalent the dialog reflows and scrolls internally without page-level horizontal scroll. The dialog must not be a fixed pixel width. At narrow viewports the dialog should approach full-screen rather than hiding controls.\n- **Focus not obscured (WCAG 2.4.11):** if the dialog has a sticky header/footer, scrolling to a focused field must not leave it hidden behind them \u2014 add scroll-padding or ensure focused element scrolls clear.\n- **Reduced motion (WCAG 2.3.3 / 2.2):** open/close transitions and any spinner respect `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` \u2014 fade/scale animations are removed or reduced; the spinner becomes a static \"Submitting\u2026\" text indicator.\n- **Color scheme:** colors meet contrast in both light and dark mode if the app supports `prefers-color-scheme`.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n- **Accessible names (WCAG 4.1.2):** Close button \u2192 `aria-label=\"Close dialog\"` (NOT `title` \u2014 Known Pitfall #2). Submit/Cancel \u2192 visible text labels are their names; no extra ARIA needed.\n- **Form labels (WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2):** every input has a visible `<label for>` AND that association is programmatic. `aria-label` is never used as a *substitute* for a visible label on a form field (Known Pitfall #3).\n- **Error message clarity (WCAG 3.3.1, 3.3.3):** errors name the field and the problem and suggest a fix \u2014 \"Email is required\" / \"Enter an email address that includes an @ symbol,\" NOT \"Invalid input.\" Server failures state the reason and the recovery \u2014 \"Submission failed: that email is already registered. Try signing in instead.\"\n- **Instructions (WCAG 3.3.2):** format requirements (e.g., \"Password must be at least 8 characters\") are in a hint `<p>` associated via `aria-describedby` BEFORE the user submits, not only revealed as an error after failure (3.3.3 / error prevention).\n- **Decorative glyphs (WCAG 1.1.1):** the `\u00d7` close glyph and any error/success icons rendered as font glyphs or inline SVG are `aria-hidden=\"true\"` (the text/label carries the meaning). If icons are CSS `::before`/`::after`, prefer moving them into `aria-hidden` `<span>`s so they never leak into the a11y tree.\n- **Language (WCAG 3.1.1):** inherits page `lang`; nothing dialog-specific unless content is multilingual.\n- **Reading order (WCAG 1.3.2):** DOM order = visual order, as enforced in Phase 4.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\nAutomated tools catch maybe 30\u201340% of what matters here. Focus management, live-region announcements, and the screen-reader narrative are **invisible** to axe-core and to visual QA \u2014 they require keyboard and AT testing. The plan below is tiered, and **DOM verification is mandatory** (Known Pitfall #9).\n\n### 1. Automated (axe-core via `npx playwright test` + a11y-test skill)\n\nRun axe-core on **every state variant**, not just the default: closed, open, field-invalid, multiple-fields-invalid, submit-pending, submit-success, submit-failure, and a nested-modal state. axe will validate: dialog role/name presence, label association, `aria-describedby` id resolution, contrast, heading order, duplicate ids (critical for a reusable component rendered twice \u2014 ids must be instance-scoped). axe will NOT validate: focus trap, focus restoration, live-region announcement, keyboard operability, announcement timing.\n\n### 2. Keyboard navigation (Playwright `.spec.js` with real `page.keyboard.press()` \u2014 CDP-backed; a11y-test skill)\n\nMandatory: real keyboard events only, no synthetic `dispatchEvent`. Test cases:\n- Trigger: Enter and Space both open the modal.\n- On open, focus is on the first form field (assert `document.activeElement`).\n- Tab from the last control wraps to the first; Shift+Tab from the first wraps to the last.\n- Tab repeatedly (e.g., 10\u00d7) never lands on any element outside the dialog (assert active element is always within the dialog).\n- Escape closes the modal.\n- On close (each of: Escape, Close button, Cancel), focus returns to the trigger (assert `document.activeElement === trigger`).\n- Enter inside a text field submits the form.\n- **Nested:** open child modal, Escape closes only the child, focus returns to the control in the parent modal; the parent is still trapped.\n- Submit button while `aria-disabled` (async pending) does not double-submit.\n\n### 3. Screen reader (manual, real AT \u2014 JAWS+Chrome, NVDA+Firefox, VoiceOver+Safari)\n\nThe irreplaceable layer. Scripted checks:\n- On open, the dialog role and name are announced.\n- Background is unreachable: try to arrow/Tab/use rotor to reach page content behind the modal \u2192 must be impossible.\n- Navigate to an invalid field \u2192 hear name + required + role + \"invalid\" + error text.\n- Blur an invalid field \u2192 hear the error announced once (not on every keystroke).\n- Submit with errors \u2192 hear \"N errors, first error: \u2026\" and focus lands on the first invalid field.\n- Async submit \u2192 hear \"Submitting\u2026\" then success/failure.\n- Success \u2192 hear \"Submitted successfully.\"\n- VoiceOver-specific: confirm the dialog boundary is respected (VO interacts with `aria-modal` differently; this is exactly why we also use `inert`).\n- JAWS/NVDA forms-mode: confirm entering the modal puts the user in forms/focus mode appropriately so typing reaches the inputs.\n\n### 4. DOM verification (MANDATORY \u2014 Known Pitfall #9)\n\nInspect the **rendered** DOM (not just source/unit assertions) to confirm:\n- `aria-describedby` on each input lists ids that **actually exist** in the DOM and point at the right hint/error nodes.\n- `aria-invalid` flips to `true`/`false` on the correct input element at the right time.\n- Exactly **one** `role=\"alert\"` and **one** `role=\"status\"` per dialog instance \u2014 and when the component is rendered twice on a page, ids are unique (no duplicate `dialog-title-{id}`).\n- The background actually receives `inert` when the modal opens and loses it on close.\n- The error `<p>` is referenced even while `hidden`, and the reference still resolves when it un-hides.\n\n### 5. Visual regression\n\nFocus rings visible at 100% and 400% zoom; reflow with no horizontal scroll at 320px-equivalent; reduced-motion disables animation; error/success states render the non-color indicators (icon + text), not color alone.\n\n### Acceptance criteria (pass = all of these)\n\n1. Dialog announces as a dialog with its name in JAWS, NVDA, and VoiceOver.\n2. Focus is trapped: 10 Tabs and 10 Shift+Tabs never leave the dialog.\n3. Escape closes; focus returns to the trigger (verified by `activeElement`).\n4. Every input has a resolving visible label + `aria-describedby`; every invalid input has `aria-invalid=\"true\"`.\n5. A new error is announced exactly once on blur and on submit; NOT on every keystroke.\n6. Submit success and failure are both announced.\n7. Nested modal closes top-only on Escape with correct focus return.\n8. axe-core: zero violations across all state variants; no duplicate ids when rendered twice.\n9. 44\u00d744 close target; reflow clean at 400%.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Modal shell \u2014 role, naming, portal, open/close, `inert` background\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `components/Modal/Modal.tsx`, `components/Modal/Modal.test.tsx`, `components/Modal/useModalStack.ts`\n**Structure Stub:** the `role=\"dialog\"` + `aria-modal` + `aria-labelledby` container, portaled to body; `inert` applied to background siblings on open, removed on close.\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `role=\"dialog\"` \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2\n- `aria-modal=\"true\"` \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2\n- `aria-labelledby=\"dialog-title-{id}\"` \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1 / 2.4.6\n- `aria-describedby=\"dialog-desc-{id}\"` (optional intro) \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1\n- `inert` on background container \u2014 WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3\n**Keyboard Interactions:** Escape closes (top-only when nested).\n**Tests:** dialog role+name present; background `inert` on open / cleared on close; Escape closes; ids unique when two instances render.\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.6, 4.1.2.\n\n### Task 2: Focus trap + focus restoration + nesting stack\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `components/Modal/useFocusTrap.ts`, `components/Modal/useFocusRestore.ts`, `components/Modal/Modal.test.tsx`\n**Structure Stub:** focusable-set computation, Tab/Shift+Tab wrap, `inert`-first approach with manual-wrap fallback; per-dialog restore target on a shared stack.\n**ARIA Attributes:** none new; this is behavior. (`tabindex=\"-1\"` on the dialog if focus lands on the container.)\n**Keyboard Interactions:** Tab wraps last\u2192first; Shift+Tab wraps first\u2192last; never exits; Escape restores; nested Escape restores to parent control.\n**Focus Management Logic:** capture `activeElement` before open; restore after unmount with `setTimeout(\u2026,0)` guard; DOM-removed-trigger fallback to container/`h1`, never `body`.\n**Tests:** the full keyboard suite in Testing Strategy \u00a72, including nested.\n**WCAG Criteria:** 2.1.2, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11.\n\n### Task 3: Form field \u2014 label, required, describedby, invalid wiring\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `components/Modal/Field.tsx`, `components/Modal/Field.test.tsx`\n**Structure Stub:** `.field` block from the HTML stub \u2014 visible `<label for>`, input with `aria-required`/`aria-invalid`/`aria-describedby`, hint `<p>`, error `<p hidden>`.\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- `<label for>` visible label \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.2\n- `aria-required=\"true\"` \u2014 WCAG 3.3.2\n- `aria-invalid` (true/false) \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2\n- `aria-describedby=\"{hint} {error}\"` \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1, 3.3.1\n**Tests (incl. DOM verification):** describedby ids resolve; `aria-invalid` toggles on the right element; error `<p>` referenced even while hidden and still resolves when shown; required indicated as text not color.\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2.\n\n### Task 4: Validation engine + live-region announcements (blur, submit, async)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `components/Modal/useValidation.ts`, `components/Modal/LiveRegions.tsx`, tests\n**Structure Stub:** the single `role=\"alert\"` summary region + single `role=\"status\"` region at dialog level, present-and-empty from first render.\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n- summary `role=\"alert\"` / `aria-live=\"assertive\"` \u2014 WCAG 4.1.3\n- status `role=\"status\"` / `aria-live=\"polite\"` \u2014 WCAG 4.1.3\n- submit button `aria-disabled=\"true\"` while async-pending (stays focusable) \u2014 WCAG 4.1.2, 4.1.3\n**Logic:** debounce field validation; announce on blur + on submit, never per-keystroke; clear\u2192set to re-announce identical text; await async checks before announcing submit result; \"N errors, first error: \u2026\" on failed submit + move focus to first invalid field.\n**Tests (manual AT + automated where possible):** error announced once on blur; submit-error summary announced and focus moves to first invalid field; success/failure announced; per-keystroke does NOT announce; exactly one alert + one status region per instance; double-submit blocked while pending.\n**WCAG Criteria:** 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 4.1.2, 4.1.3.\n\n### Task 5: Visual layer \u2014 focus ring, target size, reflow, reduced motion, non-color states\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `components/Modal/Modal.module.css` (or token-driven styles)\n**Structure Stub:** two-tone `:focus-visible` ring; 44\u00d744 close target; `max-width: min(90vw, 32rem)`, scrollable dialog body; `prefers-reduced-motion` and `prefers-color-scheme` handling; error/success icon + text.\n**ARIA Attributes:** none (visual), but enforces the non-color half of 1.4.1.\n**Tests:** visual regression at 100%/400%; reflow no horizontal scroll at 320px; reduced motion disables animation; focus ring 3:1 in light+dark; close target \u226544\u00d744; error/success show icon+text.\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.4, 1.4.10, 1.4.11, 2.3.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11, 2.5.8.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus |\n|---|---|---|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Task 1 | APG Dialog mapping correct; `role`/`aria-modal`/`aria-labelledby` present and name resolves; `inert` applied to background (not just `aria-hidden`); ids instance-scoped (no duplicates when rendered twice). |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Task 2 | Focus trap actually traps (Tab AND Shift+Tab wrap; can't reach background); focus restores to trigger on every close path; nested Escape closes top-only; no `visibility:hidden` catch-22; DOM-removed-trigger fallback never strands on `body`. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Task 3 | Every input has a VISIBLE `<label>` (not `aria-label` substitute); `aria-describedby` ids resolve in rendered DOM; error `<p>` referenced while hidden; required shown as text. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Task 4 | Exactly ONE `role=\"alert\"` + ONE `role=\"status\"` per dialog (NOT inside the field loop); announces on blur+submit not per-keystroke; identical-text re-announce works; async submit awaited before announcing; failed submit moves focus to first invalid field; submit uses `aria-disabled` not `disabled` while pending. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 5 | Task 5 | Color never sole signal (error+success have icon+text); two-tone `:focus-visible` ring visible at 400% and in dark mode; close target \u226544\u00d744; reflow clean at 320px; reduced motion respected. |\n\n---\n\n### Contract Appendix (for spec-kitty-bridge WP translation)\n\n### Architecture Overview\n\nA portaled Client Component modal shell provides Dialog (Modal) semantics (`role=\"dialog\"`, `aria-modal`, `aria-labelledby`) and removes the background from the a11y tree AND tab order via `inert` (with `aria-modal` as a secondary signal). A focus-trap hook keeps Tab/Shift+Tab cycling inside the dialog (preferring native `inert` containment with a manual-wrap fallback), and a focus-restore hook + shared open-dialog stack handle nesting and return-to-trigger. Form fields associate visible labels and `aria-describedby` hint/error nodes, toggling `aria-invalid`. A single per-dialog `role=\"alert\"` summary region and `role=\"status\"` region carry blur/submit/async announcements \u2014 never per-field live regions. Validation is debounced (announce on blur + submit, never per-keystroke) and awaits async checks before announcing submit results.\n\n### Implementation Tasks\n\n#### Task 1: Modal shell \u2014 role, naming, portal, open/close, inert background\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: none\n\n#### Task 2: Focus trap + focus restoration + nesting stack\nEstimated Effort: high\nDepends on: [1]\n\n#### Task 3: Form field \u2014 label, required, describedby, invalid wiring\nEstimated Effort: low\nDepends on: [1]\n\n#### Task 4: Validation engine + live-region announcements\nEstimated Effort: high\nDepends on: [1, 3]\n\n#### Task 5: Visual layer \u2014 focus ring, target size, reflow, reduced motion, non-color states\nEstimated Effort: medium\nDepends on: [1, 3]\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 1\naxe-core on open/closed/two-instance states; DOM verification of `role=\"dialog\"`, name resolution, `inert` toggling, and id uniqueness; Escape-closes keyboard test.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 2\nReal-keyboard Playwright suite: Tab/Shift+Tab wrap, can't-exit (10\u00d7), Escape close + focus-restore on all close paths, nested top-only Escape with parent-control restore, trigger-removed fallback.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 3\nDOM verification that `aria-describedby` ids resolve, `aria-invalid` toggles on the correct element, error `<p>` is referenced while hidden and resolves when shown; visible-label presence assertion.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 4\nManual AT (JAWS/NVDA/VoiceOver) + automated: error announced once on blur, submit-error summary + focus-to-first-invalid, success/failure announcement, NO per-keystroke announcement, single alert/status per instance, double-submit blocked while async-pending.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 5\nVisual regression at 100%/400%, reflow no-horizontal-scroll at 320px, reduced-motion disables animation, focus ring 3:1 light+dark, close target \u226544\u00d744, error/success icon+text present.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 1\nDialog role + accessible name announced by JAWS/NVDA/VoiceOver; background `inert` on open and cleared on close; no duplicate ids with two instances; Escape closes.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 2\n10 Tabs and 10 Shift+Tabs never leave the dialog; Escape closes and `document.activeElement` returns to the trigger; nested Escape closes only the top dialog and restores to the parent control; trigger-removed case never strands focus on `body`.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 3\nEvery input has a resolving visible `<label for>` plus programmatic association; `aria-describedby` ids resolve in rendered DOM; invalid fields carry `aria-invalid=\"true\"`; required indicated as text.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 4\nNew error announced exactly once on blur and on submit (not per-keystroke); failed submit announces count + first error and moves focus to the first invalid field; success and failure both announced; exactly one `role=\"alert\"` and one `role=\"status\"` per dialog; submit can't double-fire while pending.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 5\nError and success states convey meaning without color (icon + text); two-tone `:focus-visible` ring visible at 400% and in dark mode; close target \u226544\u00d744 CSS px; clean reflow at 320px-equivalent; animations removed under `prefers-reduced-motion`.\n\n### Failure Modes\n\n- **Focus escapes the modal** (only `aria-hidden`, no `inert`; or stale focusable list when async errors mount) \u2192 keyboard/SR users land on background controls. Mitigated by `inert`-first containment.\n- **Focus doesn't restore** (trigger removed, or React re-render eats `.focus()`) \u2192 SR user stranded at page top. Mitigated by stored restore target + `setTimeout` guard + non-`body` fallback.\n- **Errors shown but never announced** (per-field live region inside a loop firing duplicates, or live region inserted with its content so it never fires) \u2192 mitigated by single pre-existing dialog-level regions + clear\u2192set re-announce.\n- **Per-keystroke announcement spam** \u2192 mitigated by debounce + announce-on-blur/submit only.\n- **Async submit silence** (announce success/failure before the await resolves, or never) \u2192 mitigated by awaiting the check and announcing \"Submitting\u2026/Validating\u2026\" via the polite region.\n- **Nested Escape closes everything** instead of top-only \u2192 mitigated by the dialog stack.\n- **Duplicate ids** when the reusable modal renders twice \u2192 mitigated by instance-scoped id generation; caught by axe + DOM verification.\n- **Close \"X\" too small / `title` instead of `aria-label`** \u2192 mitigated by 44\u00d744 target and `aria-label=\"Close dialog\"` with `aria-hidden` glyph.\n",
